<div class="mb-4"><span class="md-heading"># Introduction</span></div>
<p class="mb-4">Dynamic Programming (DP) is often considered one of the most challenging topics in competitive programming. However, it's essentially just <span class="md-bold">recursion with caching</span>.</p>
<p class="mb-4">In this tutorial, we will explore:</p>
<p class="mb-4">
                        1. The core concept of overlapping subproblems.<br/>
                        2. Memoization vs Tabulation.<br/>
                        3. <span class="md-link">Classic problems</span> like the Knapsack Problem.
                    </p>
<div class="mb-4"><span class="md-heading">## What is DP?</span></div>
<p class="mb-4">Imagine you have to climb a staircase with <span class="md-code">n</span> steps. You can climb 1 or 2 steps at a time.</p>
<div class="bg-slate-50 dark:bg-slate-800/50 p-4 rounded-lg font-mono text-sm border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-700 mb-6">
<span class="text-pink-500">def</span> <span class="text-blue-600 dark:text-blue-400">climb_stairs</span>(n, memo={}):<br/>
                          <span class="text-pink-500">if</span> n <span class="text-pink-500">in</span> memo: <span class="text-pink-500">return</span> memo[n]<br/>
                          <span class="text-pink-500">if</span> n &lt;= 2: <span class="text-pink-500">return</span> n<br/>
                          memo[n] = climb_stairs(n-1, memo) + climb_stairs(n-2, memo)<br/>
                          <span class="text-pink-500">return</span> memo[n]
                    </div>
<p class="mb-4">This simple recursive structure is the foundation of many complex algorithms.</p>
<br/><br/><br/>
